<DOC><DOCNO> AP880705-0218 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 1320EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a a AM-ReligionRdp Adv08   07-05 0645</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 08,0671</SECOND><NOTE>$Adv08</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, July 8, and Thereafter</NOTE><DATELINE>RICHMOND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   More than 400 plans exist among variousChristian organizations to evangelize the world by the end of thiscentury, says a key figure in steps to coordinate the efforts.   The Rev. Thomas Wang, steering committee chairman of aconsultation planned by the different groups for next January, saysmany of such past efforts have failed because of disorganization,isolation and competition.   ``What's happening now is very different,'' he said at a programcommittee meeting at headquarters of one of the major groups, theSouthern Baptist Foreign Mission Board, to plan an agenda for theworld consultation.   ``All of a sudden it seems many of God's servants all over theworld have begun to take the end of this century, not as a magicalnumber, but as a target, a goal, a stimulation for worldevangelism,'' he said.   ``There has never been an age in the history of the church thatis more qualified to tackle this task of world evangelization interms of manpower, resources, technology, communications andtransportation.</TEXT><DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Claire Randall, for 11 years general secretaryof the National Council of Churches, was installed here as nationalpresident of Church Women United for the 1988-92 quadrennium.   A Presbytertian, Ms. Randall left the council post in 1984,succeeded by the Rev. Arie Brouwer of the Reformed Church inAmerica.   Church Women United is a national ecumenical body of about500,000 Protestant, Eastern Orthodox and Roman Catholic women.</TEXT><DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The chairman of the Presidents of Major AmericanJewish Organizations says the Arab-Israel violence in Gaza and theWest Bank can be ended through territorial compromise ifPalestinians accept Israel's right to exist.   Moris B. Abram told a Sabbath congregation that ``Israelis mustconvince the Palestinians that if they recognize Israel andforswear their covenant of violence, territorial compromise becomesa realistic goal.''</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ann N. Beardslee has been appointed actingexecutive director of Church World Service, a post from which J.Richard Butler resigned in May in a conflict with the Rev. ArieBrouwer, chief executive of the National Council of Churches.   CWS is the council's relief arm. Ms. Beardslee has been itsassistant executive director.</TEXT><DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Teen-agers are using drugs less andvolunteering extensively for charitable work, according to a Galluppoll conducted for the Religious Research Center.   Only 11 percent of teen-agers admit to using marijuana, comparedto 39 percent who did so in 1978.   The survey also found that 24 percent of America's teens arevolunteering for charitable causes or social services. Those whoattend church regularly are twice as likely to volunteer time asthose who don't attend regularly _ 31 percent versus 16 percent.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The general synod of the Reformed Church inAmerica in June voted 139-132 to encourage congregations to include``baptized children at the Lord's Table.''   Previously, only professed members were invited to receive HolyCommunion.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The National Assembly of Religious Women hascommended the decision of the Notre Dame Sisters de Namur not todismiss two sisters who question Roman Catholicism's ban on allabortions.   The two sisters, Barbara Ferraro and Patricia Hussey, run ashelter for the homeless in Charleston, S.C.   The NARW applauded them for upholding the right of responsibiledissent, and calling for dialogue on a controversial moral issue.   They were among 26 nuns who came under a Vatican ultimatum to beousted or recant their signing of a 1984 New York Times ad termingdiverse Catholic views of abortion legitimate.   Cases of the others were resolved earlier, and the order of thetwo recently declined to dismiss them despite their refusal tocondemn all abortions.</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, July 8</NOTE></DOC>